{
  "doc_id": "4061",
  "text": "Dopamine is a very important biomolecule belonging to the catecholamine neurotransmitters family. A basal level of dopamine (DA) is 1 nM and 10 nM in human serum and in the brain, respectively [CITATION_1] . The deviations from the physiological concentrations of DA in the central nervous system could be a reason for many such medical conditions as depression and schizophrenia, as well as such neurodegenerative diseases as Parkinson's, Alzheimer's and Huntington's [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . For example, loss of dopamine in the brain of a Parkinson's patient is in the range from −9 to −97%; furthermore, the decrease of DA is dependent on the different brain areas [CITATION_4] . Therefore, the control of DA concentration in physiological fluids is one of the most important tasks in medical diagnosis.",
